Architecture plan for skinned Pong

Project shape
- Start with a small Vite + TypeScript web app in Issue #1, using a single
  full-screen canvas as the game surface and DOM overlays for menus, score,
  skin selection, and match-end controls.
- Keep the runtime entirely client-side. No server is needed for game state,
  persistence, or assets beyond static hosting.

Module structure
- src/main.ts: app bootstrap, canvas creation, root controller wiring.
- src/styles.css: global layout, dark neon theme, responsive sizing, CRT and
  glow effects that are cleaner in CSS than canvas.
- src/game/types.ts: shared types for vectors, rectangles, game state, screens,
  skins, inputs, score, and match configuration.
- src/game/constants.ts: base field dimensions, paddle and ball sizes, winning
  score, AI tuning knobs, palette defaults, and timing constants.
- src/game/state.ts: initial state factories, reset helpers, match lifecycle,
  scoring transitions, selected skin hydration from localStorage.
- src/game/loop.ts: requestAnimationFrame loop, delta clamping, update/render
  orchestration, pause behavior while on non-match screens.
- src/game/input.ts: keyboard listeners and normalized input state for the
  player paddle.
- src/game/physics.ts: ball movement, wall/paddle collision, bounce angles,
  score detection, and serve direction logic.
- src/game/ai.ts: opponent paddle target selection, reaction delay, max speed,
  and fairness tuning.
- src/game/render.ts: canvas rendering for field, paddles, ball, midline,
  trail, glow, and scale-to-fit transforms.
- src/game/skins.ts: canonical skin definitions and helpers to apply colors and
  effects to paddles, ball, and preview renders.
- src/ui/screens.ts: DOM screen navigation for title, skin selection, in-game
  overlay, and match-end screen.
- src/ui/score.ts: live score display binding.
- src/ui/skinPreview.ts: compact canvas or DOM preview for paddle and ball
  skins.
- src/storage.ts: localStorage keys and guarded load/save helpers.

Shared types
- Screen: "title" | "skin-select" | "match" | "match-end".
- Vec2: x/y numbers for position and velocity.
- Paddle: position, size, speed, score, skinId.
- Ball: position, radius, velocity, trail samples, skinId.
- Skin: id, label, paddleColor, ballColor, glowColor, trailColor, accentColor.
- GameState: screen, field, player, opponent, ball, score, winner, selectedSkin.
- InputState: up/down booleans.
- MatchConfig: winningScore, playerSpeed, aiSpeed, aiReaction, ballSpeed.

Issue dependencies
- #1 must establish the web app, canvas, and basic source layout.
- #2 depends on #1 and creates the loop/render/update boundaries used by all
  gameplay issues.
- #3 depends on #2 and provides visible primitives for later movement work.
- #4, #5, and #6 depend on #2/#3 and can be implemented sequentially around
  input, physics, and AI.
- #7 depends on ball movement and collision outcomes from #5.
- #8 depends on #7 score state.
- #9, #10, and #11 depend on the renderer from #3 and can layer visual polish
  without changing gameplay rules.
- #12 defines data needed by #13, #14, and #15.
- #13 depends on #12 and the screen/navigation structure.
- #14 depends on #12 and rendering hooks from #3/#9/#11.
- #15 depends on #12/#14 and storage helpers.
- #16 and #17 establish title and match-end screens around the existing match
  lifecycle.
- #18 depends on #13/#16/#17 and formalizes transitions between all screens.
- #19 depends on the complete gameplay and navigation path.
- #20 depends on #19 observations and adjusts AI constants/behavior.
- #21 depends on the full feature set and finalizes responsive and visual
  details.

Key design decisions
- Use a fixed logical play field with responsive canvas scaling. Gameplay math
  stays stable while the canvas adapts to viewport size.
- Keep game simulation state separate from rendering and DOM UI so later issues
  can modify one area without coupling regressions into the others.
- Use delta-time updates with a maximum delta clamp to avoid giant jumps after
  tab switches or pauses.
- Store skin choice locally only; no account or backend state is required.
- Treat screen navigation as explicit state transitions instead of ad hoc show
  and hide calls.
- Define skins as data, not conditionals, so previews and in-match rendering
  use the same source of truth.
- Tune AI through constants first, preserving a predictable opponent that can be
  tested and adjusted without rewriting the loop.
- Prefer canvas for game objects and CSS for full-screen overlays such as CRT
  scanlines and menu layout.
